      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Well, when it comes to a blocked pitot tube, it's not just about physical debris like ice or snow. In fact, one of the most common causes of a blocked pitot tube is actually a type of phenomenon known as \"ice nucleation\" or \"supercooling\".\n\nYou see, when air flows over the wing, it can cause the air to become supercooled, meaning it's cooled below its freezing point without actually freezing. This can happen when the air is flowing over a surface that's been cooled by the wing, or when the air is flowing through a narrow passage like the pitot tube.\n\nIn this state, the air can become supersaturated with water vapor, which can then suddenly freeze into ice crystals when it comes into contact with a surface that's below freezing. This can cause the pitot tube to become blocked by a layer of ice, which can be difficult to detect.\n\nAnother issue that can cause a blocked pitot tube is a phenomenon known as \"pilot-induced oscillation\" or \"PIO\". This occurs when the pilot makes a series of small control inputs, which can cause the aircraft to oscillate around a certain airspeed. If the pitot tube is blocked, the airspeed indicator will",
